SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
7
8
in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 8001 of Title 36, unless there
8
9
is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
9
10
A. No bill providing for a mandate impacting the health plans
10
11
in this state shall be considered or adopted by the Senate or the
11
12
House of Representatives unless there is an impact analysis of the
12
13
bill.
13
14
B. If the President Pro Tempore of the Senate or the Speaker of
14
15
the House of Representatives or his or her designee determines that
15
16
a bill contains a mandate impacting health benefit plans, he or she
16
17
shall direct the Insurance Department to conduct an impact analysis.
17
18
C. When conducting such analysis, the Department shall:
18
19
1. Analyze the proposed mandate and prepare a written report to
19
20
be returned to the President Pro Tempore of the Senate and the
20
21
Speaker of the House of Representatives; and
21
22
2. Include in such report information related to:
22
23
a. social impact:
23
24
24
Req. No. 2720 Page 2

1
(1) the extent to which the mandate addresses a
1
2
significant public health issue,
2
3
(2) the number of individuals and demographics
3
4
affected by the proposed mandate, and
4
5
(3) any anticipated impact on access to health care
5
6
services,
6
7
b. medical efficacy:
7
8
(1) a review of peer-reviewed studies, clinical
8
9
guidelines, and other scientific evidence
9
10
evaluating the effectiveness of the treatment or
10
11
service, and
11
12
(2) input from medical experts and professional
12
13
organizations as appropriate, and
13
14
c. financial impact:
14
15
(1) the estimated effect on insurance premiums for
15
16
consumers and employers,
16
17
(2) the potential cost implications for insurers,
17
18
health care providers, and state-funded programs
18
19
that provide payment for covered services, and
19
20
(3) any anticipated impact on the stability of the
20
21
state’s insurance market.
21
22
D. The Department may contract with a third-party vendor that
22
23
specializes in actuarial services, insurance mandate reviews, or
23
24
24
Req. No. 2720 Page 3

1
other services that the Department deems necessary to carry out the
1
2
provisions of this act.
2
3
E. The Department may seek the input and expertise of any
3
4
agency of this state to evaluate the potential impact to state-
4
5
funded programs that provide payment for covered services.
5
6
F. Upon return of the analysis by the Department, the
6
7
Department shall provide an electronic copy to the author of the
7
8
legislative measure and the chairs of the legislative committees to
